column10: b'b\' We need to establish a good practice in reporting issues like this. We simply **can not** keep every single issue "it does not work with FooBar site". There are millions web sites out there and sometimes the problem is with the upstream library we use (QtWebKit) and not PhantomJS own code. Unless there is a proper reduced test case

column10: b'b" I found out that the issue (still an PhantomJS issue; I remember posting another issue of the same class ( frames crashes) before; this is the same class (I forgot to mock some data for the test case
column11: that\'s why iframe loads but very quickly closes itself)): The code does:1. Main page loads and does opening dialog in iframe.2. The page in iframe loads.3. It posts parent with \'I need this data\'4. Parent posts back the data or \'data missing\'.5. If it is \'data missing\' (which it was with forgot mock)
column12: iframe posts parent \'close me\'.6. Main page does which deletes the iframe. The test
column13: driving phantomjs via ghostdriver
column14: does this:1. Makes the main page load.2. Finds and clicks on button that starts the sequence above
column15: which run in phantomjs.3. Waits for element with class \'.cboxIframe\' to appear (that succeeds).4. Finds an element with class \'.cboxIframe\'.4a. Occassionally I got \'cannot find element with class .cboxIframe\'; which is now clear was result of colorbox dialog already closing itself.5. Switches to frame by found element.5a. Occassionally I got the \'cannot switch to frame [Object object]\'; which is now similarly clear.6. Finds an element with id \'continue\' (a submit button of a form).6a. Maybe this is where I get \'command ended without output\'
column16: when the iframe was already gone.7. Click on the button via GhostdriverYou can see the code that button had to do on clicking in OP.PhantomJS crashes (because something went wrong while trying to run the click handler on button from deleted iframe). Nevertheless
column17: I think PhantomJS should return something sensible not just crash when code is being executed in already deleted iframe while Ghostdriver is still switched in it (I very hope those two JS codes; the page and the executeScript are not run in parallel (or that process of removing iframe from DOM is not parallel with code that runs within it))."'

Which operating system are you using?Linux localhost 2.6.32-431.3.1.el6.x86_64 #1 SMP Fri Jan 3 21:39:27 UTC 2014 x86_64 x86_64 x86_64 It seems to only happen with the above 64-bit version of CentOS 6
column11: not with a 32-bit version CentOS 5. What steps will reproduce the problem?Running phantomjs multiple times (we used a shell  to simulate) against a URL to produce a PDF. column13: but if we change the URL to use 127.0.0.1 instead
column14: it can sometimes go up to 50 executions before freezing. It seems to happen around the 40-60% completed

column10: b'b" @jain0709 We don\'t want you to have to downgrade.  If something worked in 1.9.x and doesn\'t in 2.0
column11: that\'s something we should fix. That said
column12: we need quite a bit more information from you before we can do anything about this.  Specifically
column13: we need to know what website provoked this error
column14: and how you were using PhantomJS to access it -not just the command line invocation
column15: but the script.  If at all possible
column16: construct a self-contained test script that we can run as and see the same problem you are.  It\'s OK if you need extra files or even a web server
column17: just explain in enough detail that we can make it happen for ourselves. Also
column18: there\'s a decent chance this is a situation where the newer Webkit in 2.0 is refusing to do something insecure when the older one would let you get away with it.  This is a guess
column19: based on the text of the error message.  I could be wrong. Also also
column20: you shouldn\'t _ever_ need to use or -that suggests to me that you have _major_ problems with the environment you\'re running PhantomJS in
column21: and you may find that this problem vanishes if you sort those out first."'

column10: b'b" @zackw The difference in the variant that I proposed above is that the customized base image is created _once_ (even better
column11: by Docker Hub so we don\'t need to waste our own CPU cycles and such) and it will be reused by any numbers of Linux static binary builds. Given that we may only need to update the system dependencies once a while
column12: I believe we don\'t need to incur that time building all those libraries statically."'

column10: b'b" On the subject of the customized base image
column11: I agree with the sentiment from @zackw that downloading source packages without a follow-up of package verification is rather risky (especially via http). An alternative that we can consider is using Debian\'s original source package. We can use and get the benefit of built-in signature verification mechanism. The drawback of using this approach
column12: which we may or may not be able to live with
column13: is that the source package might be outdated. For example
column14: Ubuntu 14.04 has the source package of libxml2 2.9.1 while the upstream project already released version 2.9.3. My pragmatic view on this subject leans towards Debian source package. What do you think @zackw?"'

b'b" Recently I saw very similar issues about weird behaviour with AJAX requests.After a small investigation I\'ve discovered that NetworkReplyProxy (and NetworkReplyTracker) are the real source of the problems. **The problem:**Wrapping all network requests has the real impact on how WebKit processses network requests (even inside the context of the WebPage!). For example
column11: synchronous AJAX requests don\'t work. Unfortunately
column12: I didn\'t dig deep inside into. But the problem is that Webkit waits forever for sync requests (or sometimes for async requests too)
column13: so they will be never completed. **Affected issues (still collecting them):**url url url url  (not sure about this one)url  (yes
column14: memory usage is affected too)url url  **Proposal solution:** revert all commits with this feature (PR is ready
column15: just give me a green light) /cc @ariya @zackw @JamesMGreene "'

column10: b'b" OK
column11: this is definitely a real regression.  The problem is that _nearly all of the text is being emitted as vector graphics._  In other words
column12: each glyph is being converted to a series of line drawing commands.  This bulks up the file
column13: but it also makes the text non-searchable
column14: non-copyable
column15: etc. I think this probably does need to get reported upstream to Qt
column16: but first we need to nail down a reproducer and figure out why it doesn\'t happen on Windows.  It would be nice to have an example HTML file -rendering as just one page
column17: and without the huge background images
column18: please! -that shows the effect.  You can confirm the effect by trying to select text in a PDF viewer.  In your phantomjs-2.1.1.pdf
column19: only the text in the footer of each page is selectable
column20: whereas in -1.9.8.pdf all of the text is selectable."'

column12: and our CSS file looked like this:  To fix the issue

column14: and running  .  Now we can change our CSS to just the following:  PhantomJS now treats Proxima Nova as a natively installed font
column15: and renders a smaller sized PDF with selectable text.  This is the right solution.  Note: I only encountered this problem on Linux. Mac OS worked fine.'"
